1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Bf4 {A rather peculiar move at first sight, but
many will probably recognize the position after 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bf4 c5 3.d5 b5 4.c4.
} (4. Bg5 {is another rare move by this bishop in Trompowsky's style:} Ne4 $1 {
Undoubtedly the best reply - Black is already fighting for the advantage.} (
4... g6 $6 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gf8g7] is not good because of} 5. Bxf6 exf6 6. cxb5
{[%cal Gf6f5,Gf8g7,Gg7a1] Indeed, Black has some compensation for the pawn,
but I like White here.} d6 (6... Bg7 7. Nc3) 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. e3 {
The best way for White to develop.} a6 10. a4 f5 {[%cal Gg7b2] The bishop is
quite good, but Black still have problems to solve.} 11. Be2 axb5 12. Bxb5 Qa5
{[%csl Rc3]} ({Black is worse after} 12... Ba6 13. O-O Nd7 14. Nd2 $16 {
[%csl Gg7][%cal Gd2c4]}) ({or} 12... Na6 13. O-O Bb7 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c7]} 14.
Bc4 Nb4 15. h3 Re8 16. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gd1d2,Gc3b5] with clear advantage
in both lines}) 13. O-O {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf3d2]} Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qxc3 15. Nd2 $14
{[%csl Ga4][%cal Gd2c4] I definitely think White has the better chances.}) (
4... Qa5+ {Another possible continuation.} 5. Nd2 ({but not} 5. Nc3 $2 {
because of} Ne4) 5... bxc4 ({A big mistake is} 5... Ne4 $2 6. b4 $1 {- the
whole point and a typical trick in this kind of position!} Qxb4 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Rb3 Qa5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga5e1]} 9. Rxb5 Qc3 10. h4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gh1h3]
Another fantastic move - Black is in serious trouble.}) 6. Bxf6 exf6 {[%cal
Gg7g6,Gf6f5]} ({worse is} 6... gxf6 $6 7. e3 Bg7 8. Bxc4 f5 9. Ne2 d6 ({
very dangerous is} 9... Bxb2 $6 {because of} 10. Rb1 Bg7 {[%cal Gb1b8]} 11. O-O
d6 12. Ng3 $40 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd1c2,Gg3h5,Gb1b3,Gb3h3,Ge3e4] with an
increasing initiative.}) 10. O-O Nd7 11. Ng3 Nb6 12. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rf5] with
